A suppletive verb; Latin vÄdÅ (â€œI goâ€) supplies the present tense and Ä«re, present active infinitive of the synonymous eÅ, supplies the future and conditional.
The all- forms derive from Middle French aller, from Old French aler (with subjunctive aill- and other forms with all-), from Vulgar Latin *alÅ (attested in the 7th century Reichenau Glosses). 
Many explanations have been proposed for the etymology of this all- stem but none has met with a unanimous agreement among philologists. The all- stem has traditionaly been explained as deriving from Latin ambulÄre via or together with ambler (compare Old Occitan amblar, Italian ambiare, Romanian umbla), but this explanation is phonologically problematic; ambler is additionally more likely a borrowing from Old Occitan. Several theories have been put forth since the 17th century to explain how ambulare could have become aller.
Since at least the 18th century, some have suggested that aller derives not from Latin but from Celtic, Gaulish *aliu, from Proto-Celtic zero grade *É¸al-. Compare Welsh elwyf (â€œI may goâ€), Cornish ellev (â€œI may goâ€), from full grade *É¸el- (see mynd for more). This theory is however phonetically problematic.
Another theory was proposed in 1934 by E.F. Parker, suggesting that aller derives from a Late Latin stem *allare which would have been formed out of allatum, past participle of adfero ("to bring"). The idiomatic phrase allatum esse ("to be brought") is recorded in Classical Latin and would have become very common in Northern France with a meaning derivation from being brought to to have been to, in which the past participle *allatus would have been taken as meaning to go and would have then inspired a new infinitive allare (allatus wouldn't have been felt any more as being the same verb as adferre due to particular dissemblance between its stems). This new stem allare would have then been used in suppletion for the Gallo-Roman verb to go as it's infinitive ire had already been forgotten (though it had already formed the future and conditional stem of this verb) and the monosyllabic forms of the present indicative conjugation had already been replaced with those of vadere.
Franco-ProvenÃ§al allar and Friulan lÃ¢ (â€œto goâ€) (compare lin (â€œwe goâ€), lÃ¢t (â€œgoneâ€)) are from the same source, whatever it may be.
